│ An analysis of the bug reveals that the SLP vectorizer's scheduling logic can           │
│ erroneously attempt to update the dependency count of an already-scheduled entity. This │
│ occurs when an instruction, such as a function call with side effects, acts as multiple │
│ types of dependencies (e.g., data, memory, and control) for the same set of             │
│ instructions. The scheduler processes these dependency types in separate loops, and     │
│ without tracking which users have already been updated, it can try to increment the     │
│ dependency count of a user that has already been fully scheduled, leading to an         │
│ assertion failure.                                                                      │
│                                                                                         │
│ To fix this, I will introduce a `SmallPtrSet` within the scheduling logic. This set     │
│ will keep track of the `ScheduleData` objects for user instructions whose dependency    │
│ counts have already been updated during the processing of a single scheduled entity.    │
│ This ensures that for any given scheduled instruction or bundle, each of its users is   │
│ processed only once, regardless of how many dependency edges (data, memory, or control) │
│ exist between them. This change prevents the redundant updates that cause the crash.    │
│                                                                                         │
│ I will now apply this fix.                                                              │
│                                                                                         │
